There's a lot to quibble about here but I don't feel like quibbling tonight. If I come back to this in the future with nitpicks in mind, let it be known that, on initial reading, I upvoted.

My favorite part is that the monkey saw physical abuse as wrong, but killing for food as, well, just a part of life. Like, the monkey doesn't have a problem eating friends and I kind of got the impression that, if it were between the monkey starving and a friend starving, the monkey wouldn't be too sad to draw the short straw.  But inflicting pain and injury out of anger? Big no-no in the monkey's book.

It's a really weird way to look at morality, but also pragmatic in a taboo sort of way.







